<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">evidence submitted by Richard Drabble QC (LAI 0083)</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This paper is concerned with the proposed abolition of the “borderline” test.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I am a QC in private practice. I was called to the Bar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in 1975 and took silk in 1995. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Between 1992 and 1995 I was on the panel of Treasury Counsel (now the “A” panel) and both before and after taking silk acted regularly for, first, the Conservative administrations under Margaret Thatcher and John Major and then the Labour administrations a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">fter the 1997 election. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This work has involved a number of high profile cases. For example, I acted for the Executive in the judicial review challenge to the Airport White Paper concerning the second runway proposal at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Stansted</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and the judicial review ch</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">allenge to the nuclear energy review. I have acted in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">test </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cases for the E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">xecutive.  O</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ne, which is relevant</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to the theme of this paper</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, concerned “formula rating” </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">R(Edison) v Secretary of State </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2003 UKHL 20</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">; 2003 2 EGLR 133)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. It</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> went to the House of Lor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ds. The allegation was that the formula rating regime constituted unlawful double taxation. The Court of Appeal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">split 2:1 in the Executive’s favour</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(Dyson LJ – now MR – dissenting). The Lords split 3:2 in the Executive’s favour (Lords Bingham and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Steyn</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> dis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">senting). Given this appellate history and the quality of the dissents I do not see how the Executive could ever have been properly advised that the case was anything other than “borderline”. I return to the significance of this in a moment.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">On the Claima</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nt’s</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> side, I have acted for claimants in a number of cases at the highest level. Just to take one example for the purposes of illustrating this point</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, I appeared for the claimant in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">R(</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Anufrijeva</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">) v Secretary of State</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 2004 1AC 604. This issue was whether a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> benefit decision could properly be regarded as being finally made before it was made public. The Court of Appeal held that it was bound by earlier authority to decide against the claimant. The House of Lords decided 4:1 in her favour, with Lord Bingham ag</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ain dissenting. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Once again, I do not see how the legal aid authorities could have been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">advised that the case was anything other than “borderline”. It did however affect a large number of claimants and under the present regime funding was properly granted o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n that basis. The lower courts (and the DWP) had become </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">wedded to a view of the law which the majority of the Lords ultimately held to be constitutionally improper. The example of binding adverse authority which those advising the claimant now seek to argu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e is wrong is very important when one is considering the impact of a proposal to abolish the “borderline” category.   </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I now retur</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n to the central point of this r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">esponse</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. I regard the proposal as being of ge</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nuine constitutional importance, and urge that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">it should be rejected on constitutional grounds. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Looking at the Edison example above and cases like it, it is obvious that the Executive should be free to test the law by defending or appealing in important test cases. I would be startled (and saddened) i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f it accepted a principle that it would not appeal or defend a decision with large resource and public interest implications</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> because of a mathematical assessment of the odds of success by its advisers. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> It would expose itself to the risk </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of the law </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">fossilising behind an adverse decision</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> at the High Court or Court of Appeal level despite a very strong sense of unease that the law was taking a wrong turning. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is no reason for not applying the same approach to cases brought by claimants. As the c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">onsultation paper and the existing text of the Merits Regulations both recognise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> “borderline cases” can </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">at present </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be funded where the prospects of success cannot be said, by reason of disputed law, to be 50% or greater but where there is a significant wid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">er public interest. This category is precisely apt to cover the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Anufrijeva</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">example above</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and a large number of other test cases</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> where the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> law is inherently uncertain precisely because the case is a test case but where there is a real chance that the courts</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> will say that the Executive is trying to hold an unreasonable line. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In my view, the honest reaction of many advocates confronted by this type of test case under the present regime has been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(and should be) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to categorise it as borderline</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. It will frequent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ly not be possible to do more than that. Given the factors that have to be taken into account (for example adverse precedent which has to be overcome) it is unrealistic to do more. The appeal mechanism described in paragraph 3.88 of the consultation paper </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">does not overcome this problem, which arises precisely out of the fact that an honest assessment of the prospects of success puts those prospects of success as better than poor (i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> it cannot be said that success is unlikely) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">but does not put them positiv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ely as high as 50/50. If the Independent Funding </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Adjudicator agrees with that assessment s/he will be bound under the proposal to refuse funding. This is highly regrettable given the fact, recognised by the paper, that these are cases </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">which concern “holdin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">g the State to account” (see the first sentence of paragraph 3.87</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of the original consultation paper</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">).</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This brings me to my final point. If implemented, these proposals threaten to produce a situation in which the Executive can always access the higher courts if the lower courts establish a proposition </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">which it wishes to challenge</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on appeal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">; but claimants d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o not have the same ability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The system will or may become institutionally “pro-executive”. In this connection, it is necessary to bear in mind the effect of a grant of public funding in providing cost protection for a claimant. In a public interest test c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ase scenario, funding of the claimant’s lawyers own fees is only part of the problem. Without public funding, the ability of a Government Department to prevent an appeal from an Executive success before the lower tribunal by threatening to seek costs if th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e claimant/appellant loses his appeal is considerable. I personally have met this problem more than once</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Thus the problem this paper</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> tries to grapple with is not solved by the claimant’s lawyers acting pro bono</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, even if this were an acceptable or robust l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ong term solution</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The problem created by the threatened abolition of the “borderline” category is compounded by the present absence </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of a proper system of costs protection outside the developing area of Aarhus case-law.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For all these reasons I re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">peat m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">y strong opposition to the abolition of the borderline test.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">12</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> September 2013 </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">    </span></p><p style="font-size:16pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:16pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:16pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> I have used the word “Claimant” both to refer to a claimant in an application for judicial review and as a proxy for all types of appellants .</span></p></body></html>